x4freetext: Pelletron.
See SAMPLE
Four irradiations were carried out for each
projectile target combination encompassing the beam
energy between 47.4 and 77.5 MeV for 12-C and between
57.8 and 93.5 MeV for 16-O.  The energies are the
average values of the incident and outgoing projectile
energies.
The irradiation time was 10 min and 2 hours for
short-lived and long-lived products respectively.
The beam current was measured using an electron
suppressed Faraday cup placed behind the target
assembly in the continuous mode.
After the irradiation the target and following
catcher foil were counted together for the gamma
activity on a standard geometry, the gamma activities
were followed for two months.
In the case of nuclides having long lived
precursor the cross sections of the parent and daughter
nuclides were obtained by a least square fit of the
daughter activity data using decay growth equation.
For nuclides having shorter lived precursors, the
contribution of precursor in the activity of the
daughter was corrected using the cross section of the
precursor measured independently.
The uncertainty on the cross sections arise
mostly from the counting statistics, detector
efficiency, target thickness and intensity measurement.
